{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7ede5c35-f3d5-449c-b2c5-82cb1b96a7e9","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but doesn't upgrade anything.\n\nSince your SDK moved forward but your workloads didn't, you need:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, also try `dotnet workload restore` from your project directory — it installs any workloads declared in your project's `global.json` or required by your target frameworks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b9468f3d-271a-4498-beb0-2cb5a77d3322","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I can answer directly.","outputTokens":247},"id":"a6e8bd65-369f-4ce3-b244-9542a38eefaf","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:45:47.249Z","parentId":"48032629-6454-47b3-bbd4-9869fc38901b"}
